 narrow political definition of citizenship to address the cultural and economic complexities of contemporary social life. Rhoads and Szelényi show how universities should be mindful of the possibilities for faculty and student involvement in the production, management, and application of knowledge, and how this in turn allows for an engagement as citizens that reflects serious considerations of the global context. Ultimately, the authors challenge universities and readers alike to consider the many transnational opportunities that are redefining citizenship today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aEducation and globalizationvCase studies. 0aEducation, HigherxPolitical aspectsvCase studies. 0aEducation, HigherxSocial aspectsvCase studies. 0aUniversities and collegesvCase studies. 0aWorld citizenship. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh1 aSzelényi, Katalin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477780340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804777803423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804777803.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles